> The pointer solution didn't have any UB issues as mentioned above. But if you still found that to be slow then there is probably some other issue besides the copying. You mentioned it's not a fast as it "should" be. What's the comparison point there? Perhaps it's just the C++ <-> Python call overhead.

I've created a py::class_ that wraps an existing function object, so I can compare the speed of using that function object alone to the speed of a wrapper that takes objects and sends pointers to them.

In other words, using the library without pybind11 is pretty normal:

```cpp
library_fxn(std::bind(fxn_obj,std::placeholders::_1_thru_n)
```

But when using pointers, I created a wrapper object (not wrapped by pybind11, but intended as glue to the c++ library I'm using):

```cpp
/*
This is defined in a header, and all the types below are wrapped in py::class_, and
the latter 2 are opaque containers.
*/
using singlepop_fitness = std::function<double(const fwdpy11::diploid_t *,
                                                   const fwdpy11::gcont_t *,
                                                   const fwdpy11::mcont_t *)>;

//This is not run thru py::class_, 
//and is used to translate a callable
//taking pointers to one taking references
struct fitness_model_sink
{ 
       const fwdpy11::singlepop_fitness f;
        explicit fitness_model_sink(fwdpy11::singlepop_fitness f_) : f(std::move(f_))
        {
        }
        inline double operator()(const fwdpy11::dipcont_t & diploid,
                        const fwdpy11::gcont_t & gametes, 
                        const fwdpy11::mcont_t & mutations) const
        {
                return f(&diploid,&gametes,&mutations);
        }
};
```

The above struct would be used like:

```cpp
//This is exposed to Python using pybind11
void function( const fwdpy11::singlepop_fitness f, other_params...)
{
    fitness_model_sink sink(f);

    //... refers to there being other 
    //params involved
    other_library_function(...,f...);
}
```

My comment re: speed is that I can mock a case where I know what "f" is doing (referring to an existing functor), and simply drop in a std::bind(functor_type(),etc.), and I find and 8-10x speedup.

But, point taken that I've not shown there isn't another unexpected copy being generated somewhere.

I'm not sure that there should be a lot of Py -> Cpp conversion going on here. (That may be wishful thinking, though.)  This callable should get applied to every individual over a long number of generations, meaning easily millions of calls.  But this is all happening on the C++ side, in the library evolving the population.

This will work:

```c++
py::list pli;
pli.attr("count")(3);
```

