@dandelionmane filed #581.

Hence, adding native support for function parameters is a priority for TensorBoard. We plan to first make TensorBoard run on a SQL-based backend (spearheaded by @jart), which will make introducing structural features like this easier.

That being said, if this is high-priority enough, we can probably implement this feature using a config file today - we'd have a proto-based API that writes a pbtxt to disk.

Might I ask what you're working on? How real time do you need it to be?

As you know, TensorBoard currently polls the event log files, which can be written by multiple hosts in a distributed training. We want to improve our latency. The thing that would help us most right now is to collect requirements from the community.

@malmaud The format of the event logs file is it's a "records file" where each record is a binary encoded [`tf.Event`](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/e6fee141e3bdde3bac5741b2aadfdd41bd2a7b24/tensorflow/core/util/event.proto#L13) protocol buffer, which contains [`tf.summary.Summary`](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/e6fee141e3bdde3bac5741b2aadfdd41bd2a7b24/tensorflow/core/framework/summary.proto#L68) protos. You can Google how to serialize protobufs in any language. The record file format is described by [record_writer.cc](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/e6fee141e3bdde3bac5741b2aadfdd41bd2a7b24/tensorflow/core/lib/io/record_writer.cc) and @zihaolucky wrote a really excellent pure Python [implementation](https://github.com/dmlc/tensorboard/blob/master/python/tensorboard/record_writer.py) of the same thing. In essence:

```cc
  // Format of a single record:
  //  uint64    length
  //  uint32    masked crc of length
  //  byte      data[length]
  //  uint32    masked crc of data
```

